                                                                                                     [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                       owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                       owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Permeability_coefficient>
                                                                                                     ] ,
                                                                                                     [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                       owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                       owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus>
                                                                                                     ] ,
                                                                                                     [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                       owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                       owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength>
                                                                                                     ] ,
                                                                                                     [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                       owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                       owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Slope,_aspect,_elevation>
                                                                                                     ] ;
                                                                                     <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Use small or large cliff models to study the stability of cliffs and steep slopes. These models can be set up in the lab or in the field to observe changes in cliffs and the occurrence of landslides by controlling slope, soil properties, and hydrological conditions." ;
                                                                                     <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Terrain simulation: In the cliff model experiment, the model needs to be prepared according to the actual terrain features. Usually a scale-down model is used to scale down the actual cliff terrain. Factors such as the inclination angle of the terrain, soil type, and vegetation cover should be considered in the preparation of the model to ensure the similarity of the model.
2. Simulate loads: In the cliff model experiment, the trigger conditions of a cliff landslide can be simulated by applying different types of loads. External loads such as natural rainfall and earthquakes can be simulated, as well as internal loads such as erosion at the foot of cliffs can be simulated to study the triggering mechanism of landslides.
3. Monitoring and recording: During the experiment, it is necessary to use appropriate instruments and sensors to monitor the changes in the displacement, stress, strain and other parameters of the soil in the model. These data can help researchers understand the response of different parts of the landslide process, so as to infer the development trend and mechanism of the landslide.
4. Result analysis and prediction: Through the analysis of experimental data, the law and mechanism of cliff landslide development can be obtained. Researchers can predict and evaluate cliff landslides based on the experimental results, which provides a scientific basis for the prevention and management of cliff landslides.""" .


