###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Culmann_diagram_method
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Culmann_diagram_method> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Empirical_model> ;
                                                                                                <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Kuhlman Diagram Method" ,
                                                                                                                                                                                 "The Culmann diagram method is an empirical method based on the diagram method for analyzing and designing the stability of slopes and slopes." ;
                                                                                                <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Tangent method: The Culmann diagram method first uses the tangent method to determine the direction of each tangent on the landslide body. The tangent line refers to the straight line tangent to the tangent of the landslide surface, which can represent the stress and strain state inside the landslide body. In a Culmann diagram, each tangent represents an internal stress state.
2. Equilibrium method: The Culmann diagram method is based on the equilibrium method for the mechanical analysis of the landslide body. According to the principle of mechanical equilibrium, the horizontal and vertical forces on the landslide body must be balanced. Through the equilibrium method, the shear force and normal stress of each tangent line on the landslide body can be calculated, as well as the magnitude of the support force and resistance.
3. Culmann diagram: In a Culmann diagram, the horizontal axis represents the height or depth of the landslide body, and the longitudinal axis represents the shear force and normal stress of the various tangents on the landslide body. According to the results of the tangent and equilibrium methods, the mechanical states of the individual tangents and the magnitude of the forces can be plotted in the Culmann diagram. By analyzing the Culmann diagram, the stability of the landslide body can be evaluated.
4. Parameter selection and fitting: When using the Culmann diagram method, it is necessary to select the appropriate parameters, fit and adjust. The choice of parameters often relies on site survey data, laboratory test results, or other engineering experience.""" .


