###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Resilience_model
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Resilience_model> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                          rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Constitutive_model> ,
                                                                                                          [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                            owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                            owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Elastic_modulus>
                                                                                                          ] ,
                                                                                                          [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                            owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                            owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus>
                                                                                                          ] ,
                                                                                                          [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                            owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                            owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Poisson's_ratio>
                                                                                                          ] ;
                                                                                          <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "The elastic model is one of the simplest constitutive models, assuming that the soil has linear elastic behavior during the elastic phase, i.e., the stress is proportional to the strain. This includes linear elastic models described by Hooke's law, as well as more complex elastic models such as elastoplastic models." ;
                                                                                          <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Hooke's Law: The elastic model assumes that the soil obeys Hooke's law, which states that there is a linear relationship between stress and strain. According to Hooke's law, there is a linear proportional relationship between the stress (stress tensor) and the strain (strain tensor) of the soil, and the proportionality constant is the elastic modulus of the soil.
2. Linear elastic constitutive equations: The elastic model uses linear elastic constitutive equations to describe the mechanical response of a soil. These equations represent the relationship between stress and strain in matrix form, where the relationship between stress and strain can be determined by the modulus of elasticity and the Poisson's ratio. For isotropic soils, elastic models typically use linear Hooke's constitutive equations.
3. Model parameters: The parameters of the elastic model mainly include the elastic modulus and Poisson's ratio. The modulus of elasticity reflects the stiffness of the soil, while the Poisson's ratio describes the volume change of the soil under force. These parameters can be determined by laboratory tests or field observations.""" .


