###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Seepage_pressure
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Seepage_pressure> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                          rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Hydrological_force> ;
                                                                                          <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> """The main characteristics of seepage pressure include:
Pore water pressure changes: The seepage of groundwater leads to changes in the pore water pressure inside the soil or rock, and this change in pressure will directly affect the strength and deformation characteristics of the soil or rock.
Seepage velocity effect: The seepage velocity of groundwater affects the magnitude of seepage pressure, and a larger seepage velocity usually leads to a larger seepage pressure.
Support and stability: In some projects, moderate seepage pressure can provide a certain degree of support, but excessive seepage pressure may lead to failure and instability of soil or rock.""" ,
                                                                                                                                                                           "The pressure generated by groundwater on the inside of the soil or rock affects the strength and deformation characteristics of the soil or rock." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Seismic_wave_propagation_test
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Seismic_wave_propagation_test> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                       rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Elastic_modulus> ;
                                                                                                       <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> "Seismic Wave Propagation Test: The seismic wave propagation test is used to determine the dynamic properties of soil or rock, including the modulus of elasticity. By introducing seismic waves into the material and recording the wave propagation velocity and vibration characteristics, an estimate of the elastic modulus can be obtained." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                       rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/c._Physical_parameters> ;
                                                                                       <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Also known as shear elastic modulus or shear modulus, it is a physical quantity that describes the ability of a solid material to resist shear deformation. In the mechanics of materials, the shear modulus represents the unit strain produced by a material when subjected to a unit shear stress per unit area. The shear modulus is usually denoted by the symbol G" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                        rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/c._Physical_parameters> ;
                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Tensile strength refers to the maximum stress value that a rock can withstand under tensile stress, in megapascals (MPa)" ,
                                                                                                                                                                         "The maximum stress that a rock can withstand under shear stress" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_test
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_test> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                    rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Coefficient_of_friction> ,
                                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Cohesion> ,
                                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Elastic_modulus> ,
                                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Internal_friction_angle> ,
                                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus> ,
                                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength> ;
                                                                                    <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> "Shear Test: A shear test can be used to determine the shear strength and elastic modulus of a soil or rock. In shear tests, horizontal and vertical loads are applied, and the strain and displacement of the material are recorded, and the value of the elastic modulus can be calculated.。" ,
                                                                                                                                                                                    "Shear Test: In a shear test, a horizontal shear force is applied to the rock surface to measure the normal force in the vertical direction using the appropriate specimen shape and test device. By varying the ratio of the shear force to the normal force, the coefficient of friction on the rock surface can be calculated." ,
                                                                                                                                                                                    "Shear Test: The shear test is a commonly used experimental method to determine the shear strength parameters of soil or rock, including cohesion and friction angle. In direct shear tests, the value of the cohesive force can be calculated by applying horizontal and vertical loads, as well as by recording the strain and displacement of the soil or rock sample." ,
                                                                                                                                                                                    "Shear test: A common method is to perform a direct shear test or a triaxial shear test. In the direct shear test, the rock sample is cut into the appropriate geometry, and then the shear stress in the horizontal direction is applied, the normal stress in the vertical direction is measured, and the internal friction angle can be determined by changing the ratio of the shear stress to the normal stress." ,
                                                                                                                                                                                    "Shear test: In a shear test, a rock sample is placed in a shear testing machine and a shear force perpendicular to the shear plane is applied until the rock sample cracks. By measuring the maximum shear strength of a rock sample, the shear strength of the rock can be obtained." ,
                                                                                                                                                                                    "Shear test: In a shear test, a rock sample is placed in a shear testing machine, a shear force perpendicular to the shear plane is applied, and the strain is measured. The shear modulus of the rock is calculated from the experimental data." ;
                                                                                    rdfs:comment "" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Simple_dimensional_analysis
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Simple_dimensional_analysis> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                     rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/d._Mechanical_model> ;
                                                                                                     <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> """Terrain parameters: Includes slope, aspect, elevation, and more. These parameters can be obtained from topographic survey data, digital elevation models (DEMs) or satellite remote sensing images, for example.

Soil or rock mechanical parameters: including shear strength, elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio, etc. These parameters can be obtained from indoor trials, outdoor trials, or data from existing literature and databases.

Hydrological parameters: including rainfall, rainfall intensity, rainfall duration, etc. These parameters can be obtained from meteorological observation data, meteorological records or relevant hydrological data.

Hydrogeological parameters: including permeability, permeability coefficient, etc. These parameters can be obtained from hydrological observations, hydrological experiments, or data from existing literature and databases.

Vegetation parameters: including vegetation coverage, root characteristics, etc. These parameters can be obtained through vegetation surveys, remote sensing image interpretation, or related literature.

Groundwater parameters: including groundwater level, hydrological conditions, etc. These parameters can be obtained from hydrological observations, hydrological surveys or associated hydrological data.

Historical landslide data: including the location, scale, and impact of the landslide. These data can be obtained through historical records, satellite remote sensing imagery or relevant disaster reports and documentation.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Simulate_a_sloping_slope
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Simulate_a_sloping_slope> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                  rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Physical_model> ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Boundary_parameters>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Cohesion>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Internal_friction_angle>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Material_parameters>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Permeability>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Permeability_coefficient>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength>
                                                                                                                  ] ,
                                                                                                                  [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                    owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                    owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Slope,_aspect,_elevation>
                                                                                                                  ] ;
                                                                                                  <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Set up a simulated slope in the laboratory or in the field, and observe the stability of the slope and the occurrence of landslides by manipulating factors such as the nature, slope and moisture of the soil." ;
                                                                                                  <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Principle of geometric similarity: The geometry of the experimental model is similar to the actual slope, that is, the proportional relationship is maintained. Size scaling is often used to ensure geometric similarity.
2. Material Similarity Principle: Experiments are carried out using soil materials that are similar to those of the actual slope. The physical and mechanical properties of the soil material should be similar to the soil or rock of the actual slope. Common materials include clay, sand, rock simulant materials, etc.
3. Setting of boundary conditions: In the experimental model, you need to set appropriate boundary conditions to simulate the actual slope. These boundary conditions can include the slope of the slope, aspect, the initial state of the soil, hydrological conditions, and so on.
4. Loading method: In the experiment, it is necessary to apply an appropriate loading method to simulate the external force action of the slope landslide. The loading method can be gravity loading, hydraulic loading, vibration loading, etc., to simulate the mechanical process in the actual landslide event.
5. Observation and measurement: During the experiment, the changes in soil displacement, deformation, stress and other parameters are monitored and recorded in real time by installing sensors and measuring equipment. Commonly used observation methods include displacement gauges, strain gauges, manometers, inclinometers, etc.""" .


