###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Terzahi-Wegman_model
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Terzahi-Wegman_model> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                              rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Empirical_model> ,
                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Compressive_modulus>
                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Compressive_strength>
                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Internal_friction_angle>
                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Material_parameters>
                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength>
                                                                                                              ] ;
                                                                                              <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Terzaghi-Wegman model" ,
                                                                                                                                                                               "The Terzaghi-Wegman model is used to calculate the pore water pressure and effective stress of the soil, and is suitable for landslide analysis considering hydrological conditions." ;
                                                                                              <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """The Terzaghi-Wegman model assumes that the soil has plastic fluidity, and that the strain state of the soil is generated along an equivalent stress cylinder surface with a radius of 45 degrees during loading. Due to the plastic deformation of the soil, some spatial stresses will be generated on the equivalent stress cylinder surface, which can be decomposed into normal stress and shear stress. In the Terzaghi-Wegman model, these stress components are taken into account separately in the calculation of friction and end resistance.

Specifically, in the Terzaghi-Wegman model, friction consists of two parts: side friction and face friction. The lateral friction is generated by the friction between the soil and the side of the foundation, and is calculated as follows: f = Nc * σ' * tan(φ), where Nc, σ' and φ represent the unconfined compressive strength coefficient, effective stress and internal friction angle of the soil, respectively. The end face friction is generated by the friction of the soil on the end face of the foundation, and the calculation formula is: q = Nq * σ' * tan(φ), where Nq represents the unconfined shear strength coefficient of the soil.

The end resistance is caused by the deformation of the soil in the lower part of the foundation, and is calculated as: p = Nc * σ', where Nc and σ' are the same as above. This formula assumes that the soil presents a linear stress-strain relationship during the load-bearing process, that is, when the stress increases, the strain of the soil will also increase, but the growth rate is constant.

The total load-bearing capacity is equal to the sum of the frictional force and the end resistance, i.e.: qult = f + p. The Terzaghi-Wegman model is suitable for homogeneous, isotropic soils and assumes that the foundation surface is flat, horizontal, and sufficiently hard.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/The_Mohr-Cullom_model
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/The_Mohr-Cullom_model> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                               rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Constitutive_model> ,
                                                                                                               [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                 owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                 owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Cohesion>
                                                                                                               ] ,
                                                                                                               [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                 owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                 owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Internal_friction_angle>
                                                                                                               ] ,
                                                                                                               [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                 owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                 owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength>
                                                                                                               ] ,
                                                                                                               [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                 owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                 owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Slope,_aspect,_elevation>
                                                                                                               ] ;
                                                                                               <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Mohr-Coulomb model" ,
                                                                                                                                                                                "The Mohr-Coulomb model describes the strength and deformation characteristics of geotechnical materials based on friction angles and cohesion, and is often used to analyze the stability of rock and soil masses and predict possible sliding behaviors." ;
                                                                                               <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Stress state: The Mohr-Coulomb model describes the behavior of the soil based on the stress state. In the two-dimensional plane, considering the principal stress σ1 and the shear stress τ, a Mohr stress circle can be constructed to represent the stress state of the soil.
2. Strength Criterion: The Mohr-Coulomb model uses the linear tangent rule to describe the strength of the soil. The strength criterion limits the shear behavior of the soil by means of a linear tangent. On a Mohr stress circle, the strength criterion consists of a line with a slope of tan(φ) and a line with an intercept of c.
3. Cohesion c: Cohesion c is a parameter in the Mohr-Coulomb model that represents the suction and cohesion forces inside the soil. It refers to the fact that the soil still has a certain strength when there is no shear stress.
4. Internal friction angle φ: The internal friction angle φ is another parameter in the Mohr-Coulomb model that indicates the shear resistance of the soil. It refers to the angle between the principal stress and the shear stress when the soil begins to undergo shear failure.
5. Failure criterion: According to the Mohr-Coulomb model, failure occurs in the soil if and only if the shear stress exceeds the upper bound defined by the strength criterion. On the Mohr stress circle, the failure criterion corresponds to the intersection of the tangent line and the axis of the maximum principal stress.""" .


