                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "The boundary element method is used to analyze the stability and sliding behavior of the landslide body by solving the integral equation on the boundary of the problem domain to obtain the displacement and stress field of the internal region." ;
                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> "Tagdarri, Elimente, Mesode, Isousetto, Analizet, Stabilit, Tieandes, Lidin, Behaveo, Bentrandes, Lied, Bodi, Bisolwente, Integra Equatien, Ent, Bangdarri, Bent, Probulum, Domanto, Obutant Di Plasement, Anderstrosfeld, Bent, Internarre." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Discrete_Element_Method_(DEM)）
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Discrete_Element_Method_(DEM)）> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                        rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Numerical_simulation_model> ,
                                                                                                                        [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                          owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Boundary_parameters>
                                                                                                                        ] ,
                                                                                                                        [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                          owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Cohesion>
                                                                                                                        ] ,
                                                                                                                        [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                          owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Elastic_modulus>
                                                                                                                        ] ,
                                                                                                                        [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                          owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Internal_friction_angle>
                                                                                                                        ] ,
                                                                                                                        [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                          owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Material_parameters>
                                                                                                                        ] ;
                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "The discrete element method is used to analyze the mechanical behavior and sliding mechanism of the landslide body by simulating the motion and interaction of the particles and considering the contact and friction between the particles inside the landslide body." ;
                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Particle discretization: The discrete element method treats a granular material or rock and soil mass as a discrete system composed of a large number of discrete particles or elements, each of which has a certain mass, shape, and interaction force.
2. Model particle-particle interactions: Model the interaction forces between each pair of particles, which can include elastic forces, friction, cohesion, etc. between particles. These interaction force models can be set according to the properties of the granular material and the actual situation.
3. Time Integration: The evolution of a particle system in time is simulated by numerical integration methods (such as explicit or implicit integration), and the position, velocity, and force experienced by the particles at each moment are calculated.
4. Collision and contact: In the discrete element method, the collision and contact between particles need to be considered, and the interaction force between particles is calculated according to the collision model and the contact force model.
5. Result analysis: Through the simulation of the evolution process of the particle system, the displacement, velocity, stress distribution and other information of the particles can be obtained, so as to analyze the formation mechanism and development law of the landslide.""" .


