                                                                                                                                          owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Slope,_aspect,_elevation>
                                                                                                                                        ] ;
                                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "The fusion discrete and continuous method divides the landslide body into two parts, discrete particles and continuous media, and considers the interaction between them. The discrete part uses the discrete element method to describe the movement and interaction of particles, while the continuous part uses the finite element method or the finite difference method to describe the deformation and seepage process of the continuum medium." ;
                                                                                                                        <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Discrete model: The fusion of discrete and continuous methods treats a landslide as a system composed of discrete particles or blocks. Each particle or block has its own geometry, physical properties, and interactions. The discrete model simulates the deformation and failure process of a landslide body by describing and tracking the movement and interaction of each particle or block.
2. Continuous model: At the same time, the fusion discrete and continuous method also takes into account the continuity characteristics of the landslide. By introducing the concept of continuum in the discrete model, such as the stress and strain fields of the soil, it can be used to describe the continuous behavior within the landslide body. Continuum models are typically modeled using continuum mechanics theories such as elastic mechanics or elastoplastic mechanics.
3. Coupling relationship: The key to fusing the discrete and continuous method is to establish the coupling relationship between the discrete model and the continuous model. By associating the motion and interaction of discrete particles or blocks with the stresses and strains of a continuum medium, the information transfer and energy balance between discrete and continuous can be achieved.
4. Numerical solving: The fusion of discrete and continuous methods uses numerical methods to solve the model. Discrete models are usually solved using methods such as Discrete Element Method (DEM) or Particle-Fluid Simulation (PFS), while continuous models are solved using methods such as Finite Element Method (FEM) or Boundary Element Method (BEM). By coupling the discrete model and the continuous model, the distribution of physical quantities such as stress, strain and displacement in the landslide body can be obtained.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Grasine_finite_element_method_(Ksm)）
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Grasine_finite_element_method_(Ksm)）> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                                              rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Numerical_simulation_model> ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Elastic_modulus>
                                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Permeability>
                                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Permeability_coefficient>
                                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_modulus>
                                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Shear_strength>
                                                                                                                              ] ,
                                                                                                                              [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                                                                                                owl:onProperty <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/requiredParameters> ;
                                                                                                                                owl:someValuesFrom <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Poisson's_ratio>
                                                                                                                              ] ;
                                                                                                              <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "Grasine is an extension of the finite element method that deals with irregular geometries such as cracks and interfaces by introducing additional degrees of freedom." ;
                                                                                                              <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Finite Element Method: The Grassiin Finite Element Method is based on the finite element method and is a numerical analysis method widely used in the field of structural analysis and soil mechanics. The finite element method discretizes a continuous object into a finite number of elements, and the physical behavior within each element can be described by displacements and stresses on the nodes. In landslide mechanics, the Grassiein finite element method uses a finite element mesh to discretize the landslide body to simulate the deformation and failure process of the landslide.
2. Grahein Model: The Grahiin finite element method uses the Grahein model, which is an ideal elastoplastic model that takes into account the effects of gravity. The model assumes that the soil is an elastic-fully plastic material, and includes an elastic and plastic phase in the calculation. The elastic phase is described by the linear elastic theory, while the plastic phase is described by the Moore-Coulomb criterion or the Moore-Coulomb-Debs criterion.
3. Gravitational action: The Grahiin finite element method considers the gravitational interaction between soil particles within the landslide body. By introducing gravity loads into the model, the external gravity of the landslide can be simulated and the stability of the landslide can be analyzed.
4. Boundary and Initial Conditions: When performing a Grasiin finite element analysis, the appropriate boundary conditions and initial conditions need to be given. Boundary conditions include constraints and load conditions that model the interaction of the landslide body with its surroundings. The initial condition describes the stress and displacement state of the landslide at the beginning.
5. Numerical solving: The Grassiein finite element method uses numerical methods to solve the model. By discretizing the landslide body, a finite element mesh is established, and based on the Grahiin model and the corresponding boundary conditions, the physical quantities such as displacement and stress in each element are iteratively calculated. Through numerical solving, the stress, strain and displacement of the landslide can be obtained, and then the stability and deformation behavior of the landslide can be evaluated.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Grid_Method_(GM)
<http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Grid_Method_(GM)> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                                                                          rdfs:subClassOf <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/Numerical_simulation_model> ;
                                                                                          <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/comment> "The lattice method is a method of discretizing a region into a regular or irregular grid, by establishing an equation representing a physical quantity on the grid node, and then obtaining an approximate solution by numerical solving method. In landslide simulations, it can be used to account for the deformation and displacement of the soil." ;
                                                                                          <http://www.semanticweb.org/94180/ontologies/2023/3/untitled-ontology-8/principle_of_the_model> """1. Meshing: First, the landslide area is divided into regular grids or lattices, each representing a discrete location. The mesh can be 2D (planar simulation) or 3D (volume simulation), depending on the requirements of the problem.
2. Equation establishment: At each grid point, an equation is established to describe the mechanical behavior of the landslide, such as momentum equilibrium, stress-strain relationship, etc. These equations can be selected and set according to different models and assumptions, such as elastic models, plastic models, etc.
3. Boundary conditions: In the simulation, boundary conditions need to be set to describe the interaction between the landslide body and the external environment. Boundary conditions can include applied external forces, displacement boundary conditions, and so on.
4. Numerical solving: The lattice method usually uses numerical methods to discretize and solve equations. Discretization converts continuous equations into discrete difference or integral forms, and then uses numerical methods (such as finite difference method, finite element method, etc.) to solve for displacement, velocity, and stress at each lattice point.
5. Result analysis: Through the analysis of the simulation results, the displacement, velocity, stress distribution and other information of the landslide body can be obtained, so as to evaluate the stability of the landslide and predict the possible landslide behavior.""" .


